  "text": "The Node.js ESM loader and CJS-ESM interop bridge is a sophisticated system that manages ES module loading while maintaining backward compatibility with CommonJS. Here are the key components:\n\n**Entry Point Detection and Module Type Resolution:**\nThe migration process begins at `lib/internal/modules/run_main.js`. The `executeUserEntryPoint()` function determines whether to load the entry point as ESM or CJS using `shouldUseESMLoader()`, which checks for:\n- Explicit --experimental-default-type=module flag\n- .mjs/.mts file extensions\n- type: \"module\" in nearest package.json\n- Custom loaders or --import flags\n\nIf ESM is needed, `runEntryPointWithESMLoader()` initializes the cascaded loader via `getOrInitializeCascadedLoader()`.\n\n**Module Loader Architecture:**\nThe `ModuleLoader` class in `lib/internal/modules/esm/loader.js` is the core machinery handling module resolution, loading, and caching. It maintains:\n- `#resolveCache`: Registry of resolved specifiers (via ResolveCache from module_map.js)\n- `loadCache`: Registry of loaded modules (via LoadCache from module_map.js)\n- `translators`: Collection of format-specific translators for 'module', 'commonjs', 'json', 'wasm', and 'builtin' formats\n\nThe `CustomizedModuleLoader` class wraps the ModuleLoader to support custom hooks, while the `HooksProxy` and `Hooks` classes in `lib/internal/modules/esm/hooks.js` implement the user-defined loader interface.\n\n**Specifier Resolution:**\nThe `defaultResolve()` function in `lib/internal/modules/esm/resolve.js` implements package.json exports and imports resolution. It delegates to:\n- `packageResolve()`: Resolves bare specifiers using package.json\n- `moduleResolve()`: Handles relative and absolute paths\n- `packageExportsResolve()` and `packageImportsResolve()`: Implement conditional exports/imports\n- `resolveAsCommonJS()`: Falls back to CJS resolution for compatibility\n\n**Module Loading and Translation:**\nOnce resolved, the `defaultLoad()` function in `lib/internal/modules/esm/load.js` fetches the module source. The `translators` map in `lib/internal/modules/esm/translators.js` contains format-specific handlers:\n- 'module': Compiles JavaScript via `compileSourceTextModule()`\n- 'commonjs': Wraps CJS modules via `createCJSModuleWrap()` and `loadCJSModule()`\n- Other formats: Handled through specialized translators\n\n**CJS-ESM Interop:**\nThe `lib/internal/modules/cjs/loader.js` file implements the fallback for ESM-to-CJS bridging. The `finalizeEsmResolution()` function converts ESM-resolved paths to actual file paths and validates them, ensuring CJS modules can be required from ESM.\n\n**Module Job and Linking Pipeline:**\nThe `ModuleJob` and `ModuleJobSync` classes in `lib/internal/modules/esm/module_job.js` manage the module lifecycle:\n- Constructor: Creates a ModuleJob wrapping a ModuleWrap (C++ binding)\n- `_link()`: Asynchronously links dependencies by resolving and loading all module requests\n- `_instantiate()`: Performs deep instantiation of the dependency graph\n- `run()`: Evaluates the module and its dependencies\n\nThe synchronous variant, `ModuleJobSync`, is used for loading CJS modules within ESM via `runSync()`.\n\n**Native ModuleWrap Binding:**\nThe `ModuleWrap` class in `src/module_wrap.cc` and `src/module_wrap.h` is the C++ binding to V8's Module API:\n- Wraps V8 Module objects and manages their lifecycle\n- Implements `link()`: Connects module requests to their resolved modules\n- Implements `evaluate()` and `evaluateSync()`: Executes module code in the V8 context\n- Manages the resolution cache and synthetic module evaluation steps\n- Provides `CompileSourceTextModule()`: Compiles source code into V8 modules\n- Manages host-defined options for module instantiation\n\n**Import Meta and Format Detection:**\nThe `initializeImportMeta()` function in `lib/internal/modules/esm/initialize_import_meta.js` sets up `import.meta` properties, while `getFileProtocolModuleFormat()` in `lib/internal/modules/esm/get_format.js` detects module formats based on file extensions and package.json configuration.\n\nThis architecture enables Node.js to seamlessly execute both ES modules and CommonJS modules, with proper isolation and format detection, while maintaining full backward compatibility."
}

